You can definitely chain them, but honestly, for logging requests in Axum/Actix, you usually set up an HTTP handler that wraps the response. Here's a cleaner pattern: 

```rust
use actix_web::middleware::{Next, LogRequest};
use std::sync::Arc;

struct MyApp(Arc<AppState>);

pub async fn handle_request(
    req: ActixRequest,
    next: Next<ActixRequest>,
) -> Result<Response<'static>, AxumError> {
    let method = req.method().clone();

    // Log the incoming request details here
    log::info!("Incoming: {} - {}", method, req.uri());

    Ok(next.run(req))// Pass through to your actual route handler
}
```
The `LogRequest` middleware just intercepts every HTTP request before it goes into your application logic. You can use this alongside a custom middleware or even within the handler itself if you want more control over how the logs are formatted.

That's where error handling in Axum/Actix gets real interesting: 

```rust
async fn handle_get_users(state: Arc<AppState>) -> Result<Json<Vec<User>>, AxumError> {
    let users = state.users.clone();

    // This is the tricky part. If we call an async block that returns an Err, 
    // we can't just return it directly because of how async functions work in Rust.
    // We have to convert our error into a special AxumError type.

    Ok(Json(users))
}

#[derive(Axum::From)]
pub struct DatabaseError(pub String);

impl From<DatabaseError> for AxumError {
    fn from(err: DatabaseError) -> Self { err }
}
```
The key takeaway is that when something inside a non-async handler fails, you can't throw back the error. You have to wrap it in an `Axum::from` block and then convert your custom error type into the standard `AxumError`. This way, downstream middleware or request tracing can pick up that error and format the log message properly.

